Here are some common kubectl commands for managing deployments in Kubernetes:

kubectl create deployment <deployment-name> --image=<image-name>: This command creates a new deployment with the specified name and container image.

kubectl get deployments: This command lists all deployments in the current namespace.

kubectl describe deployment <deployment-name>: This command displays detailed information about the specified deployment, including the number of replicas, the container image, and the deployment strategy.

kubectl scale deployment <deployment-name> --replicas=<number-of-replicas>: This command scales the specified deployment to the specified number of replicas.

kubectl rollout status deployment <deployment-name>: This command checks the rollout status of the specified deployment.

kubectl set image deployment <deployment-name> <container-name>=<image-name>: This command updates the container image for the specified container in the specified deployment.

kubectl delete deployment <deployment-name>: This command deletes the specified deployment.
